        </div>

        <div class="plans">
<p>Downsizing from a 3.8-litre to a 3.0-litre engine and adding a hybrid system should also make the new car slightly more fuel efficient than the current R35 model. This will hardly be a headline grabbing statistic, however – we’re more interested in seeing whether it can better the Tesla Model S P100D’s incredible 0-62mph sprint time.</p>
<p>Nissan isn’t expected to reveal a new GT-R before 2018 and we may have to wait until 2020 before we see it in dealerships. The new hybrid system could add a significant chunk to the asking price, however, potentially pushing entry-level cars close to the £100,000 mark. That said, it’ll still probably be cheaper than rivals from Porsche and Lamborghini.</p>
        </div>



